In particular, when formula_119 then formula_7 is an abelian group since any non-trivial group element is of order formula_105 or formula_122 If some element formula_1 of formula_7 is of order formula_125 then formula_7 is isomorphic to the cyclic group of order formula_125 hence abelian. On the other hand, if every non-trivial element in formula_7 is of order formula_129 hence by the conclusion above formula_130 then formula_131 or formula_122 We only need to consider the case when formula_133 then there is an element formula_2 of formula_7 which is not in the center of formula_78 Note that formula_137 includes formula_2 and the center which does not contain formula_2 but at least formula_105 elements. Hence the order of formula_137 is strictly larger than formula_129 therefore formula_143 therefore formula_2 is an element of the center of formula_80 a contradiction. Hence formula_7 is abelian and in fact isomorphic to the direct product of two cyclic groups each of order formula_147

==Conjugacy of subgroups and general subsets==

More generally, given any subset formula_148 (formula_149 not necessarily a subgroup), define a subset formula_150 to be conjugate to formula_149 if there exists some formula_9 such that formula_153 Let formula_154 be the set of all subsets formula_150 such that formula_156 is conjugate to formula_157

A frequently used theorem is that, given any subset formula_158 the index of formula_159 (the normalizer of formula_149) in formula_7 equals the cardinality of formula_154:
formula_163

This follows since, if formula_164 then formula_165 if and only if formula_166 in other words, if and only if formula_167 are in the same coset of formula_168

By using formula_169 this formula generalizes the one given earlier for the number of elements in a conjugacy class.

The above is particularly useful when talking about subgroups of formula_78 The subgroups can thus be divided into conjugacy classes, with two subgroups belonging to the same class if and only if they are conjugate.
Conjugate subgroups are isomorphic, but isomorphic subgroups need not be conjugate. For example, an abelian group may have two different subgroups which are isomorphic, but they are never conjugate.

==Geometric interpretation==

Conjugacy classes in the fundamental group of a path-connected topological space can be thought of as equivalence classes of free loops under free homotopy.

==Conjugacy class and irreducible representations in finite group==

In any finite group, the number of nonisomorphic irreducible representations over the complex numbers is precisely the number of conjugacy classes.

